  <RulesElement name="Glass from the Sand" type="Ritual" internal-id="ID_TIV_RITUAL_MAGICAL_MEMORIES_100_1" source="Magical Memories from Beyond: Forgotten Rituals" revision-date="1/11/2011 3:22:33 PM">
    <Flavor> You have delimited a perimeter in the sand of the beach, knowing well that its main constituent, that is to say silica, was the basic element required by the ritual, followed by natron and lime, which you've added up. Then you've brought a flame. The heat has intensified tenfold, hundredfold, fueled by the ritual's magic, and the glass objects you have visualized in your mind have slowly emerged from this rudimentary matrix. </Flavor>
    <specific name="Category"> Creation </specific>
    <specific name="Key Skill"> Arcana or Nature </specific>
    <specific name="Component Cost"> Special </specific>
    <specific name="Duration"> Permanent or until destroyed </specific>
    <specific name="Level"> 2 </specific>
    <specific name="Time"> 8 hours </specific>
    <specific name="Market Price"> Variable (According to Object Size) </specific>
    <specific name="Prerequisite" />
    <specific name="type"> Ritual </specific>
From an ample mixture containing all the ingredients required in glass-making - or else from a sufficient quantity or recycled glass - combined with an intense magical heat you create permanent objects made of translucent or transparent glass, just like a glassblower or glass-maker would. The dimension of the objects - as well as the number created - are determined by the Arcana or Nature check result and they can be anything you want, ranging from the simplest bottles to the most awesome objects d'art. The performer knows if he has reached the desired size before the ritual's completion and can elect to abort the process if he wishes so or select more modest objects instead. Stopping midstream means that no components are expended; salvaging them could prove to be quite problematic however, the secondary ingredients being mixed up with the sand as part of the ritual. On the other hand, by recycling the matrix the caster can elect to start the process anew with the same medium over and over again until he has obtained the right result, which undeniably cost less but can prove excessively time consuming. 
The glass can be colored if the performer of the ritual wishes so by adding a metal oxide (or else) according to the desired hue he wants, though this operation doubles the ritual's cost (same holds true for the market price). The ritual has limitations however; only monochrome objects can be realized, though many shades of the same color can adorn the items simultaneously. Patterns, such as spirals, strips, or waves can improve the appearance of the items as desired, but it is absolutely impossible to create objects that require enameling or that are engraved. On the other hand, the products thus obtained can be enhanced later on with the right techniques.

&lt;table&gt;Arcana or Nature Check Result	Object: Size and Number Created	Component Cost	Market Price
9 or lower	Tiny (1d20)	1gp	2gp (Tiny)
10-14	Tiny (2d20) or Small (1d12)	5gp	10gp (Small)
15-19	Tiny (3d20) or Small (2d12) or Medium (1d10)	25gp	50gp (Medium)
20-24	Tiny (4d20) or Small (3d12) or Medium (2d10) or Large (1d8)	50gp	100gp (Large)
25-29	Tiny (5d20) or Small (4d12) or Medium (3d10) or Large (2d8) or Huge (1d6)	100gp	500gp (Huge)
30 or higher	Tiny (6d20) or Small (5d12) or Medium (4d10) or Large (3d8) or Huge (2d6) or Gargantuan (1d4)	500gp	500gp (Gargantuan)&lt;/table&gt;

Although this ritual has not been originally conceived as a defensive means many spellcasters who have experimented with it have discovered that any creature that crosses the zone where the glass objects are forming suffer 1d6 fire damage for each round they spend within the area, which renders this ritual useful to impede movements in a given zone for a very long period of time.

&lt;table&gt;Object Size	Perimeter Size
Tiny	1 square
Small	1 Square
Medium	1 Square
Large	4 squares
Huge	9 squares
Gargantuan	16 squares&lt;/table&gt;
</RulesElement>
